AI-Assisted Data Reconciliation for TARGO–OLB Data Migration

1. Background

Since January 2026, Oldenburgische Landesbank (OLB) has become part of the TARGO Deutschland Group, following its acquisition by Crédit Mutuel Alliance Fédérale through TARGO Deutschland. As part of the post-merger integration, a comprehensive IT portfolio consolidation is underway, covering:

· Applications – Rationalization and integration of legacy and modern systems

· Infrastructure – Consolidation across hosting platforms and environments

· IT Support & Delivery Services – Alignment of operational models and support structures

· Data – Unification of databases, schemas, and data assets

To enable seamless business operations and reporting, a TARGO–OLB Data Migration Program has been initiated. This program focuses on harmonizing and consolidating data across both organizations into unified target systems.

2. Problem Statement

The data migration effort involves a complex hybrid IT landscape, including:

· Legacy/Mainframe systems (applications, copybooks, batch files)

· Satellite open systems (distributed applications interacting with mainframes)

This introduces key challenges:

· Heterogeneous data formats (EBCDIC, flat files, relational schemas)

· Complex transformation logic derived from business rules

· Inconsistencies between source and target data models

· High risk of data loss, duplication, or misalignment during migration

Therefore, a robust, scalable, and intelligent reconciliation mechanism is required to ensure:

· Completeness (no data loss)

· Accuracy (correct transformation and mapping)

· Consistency (alignment across systems)

3. Reconciliation Process Overview

The reconciliation framework is designed as an AI-assisted validation pipeline.

3.1 Inputs to the Reconciliation Engine

The process ingests the following key inputs:

1. Source Data Files

o Mainframe extracts (files, copybooks)

o Open system data feeds (CSV, JSON, relational extracts, schemas)

2. Target Schema / Copybooks

o Target data model definitions

o copybooks and/or relational schemas

3. Business Rules (Plain Text)

o Defined by Business Analysts (BAs)

o Include transformation logic, validations, and domain rules

3.2 AI/LLM Integration

The solution leverages a Gen AI-based LLM (Mistral) for intelligent automation across key steps:

a. Data Profiling

· Generates summary statistics:

o Record counts

o Field distributions

o Null/invalid value patterns

· Produces source vs target profiling reports

b. Schema Understanding

· Interprets:

o Copybooks

o Relational schemas

· Normalizes metadata across formats

c. AI-Assisted Mapping Generation

· Automatically derives mappings between:

o Source fields → Target fields

· Resolves:

o Naming differences (cust_id → customer_id)

o Data type mismatches

o Semantic equivalence

Output:

JSON

{

"source_field": "cust_id",

"target_field": "customer_id",

"transformation": "direct_map"

}

d. Transformation Logic Generation

· Converts plain-text business rules into:

o Executable logic (Python / SQL / .NE.NET)

· Leverages GitHub Copilot to assist developers in integrating logic into pipelines

e. Reconciliation Rule Generation

· Automatically defines validation checks:

o Record count reconciliation

o Field-level validation

o Aggregation checks

o Referential integrity checks

3.3 Execution Layer

While Mistral handles intelligence, execution is performed via:

· .NET-based reconciliation services

· Data processing frameworks (e.g., Pandas / Spark if applicable)

· Pipelines hosted in Azure (Private Cloud)

3.4 Outputs

The reconciliation process produces:

· Mapping Documents (STTM: Source To Target Mapping)

· Transformation Logic Artifacts

· Reconciliation Reports

o Matched records

o Mismatched records

o Missing records

o Data anomalies

· Audit Logs & Traceability Reports


4. Role of GitHub Copilot

GitHub Copilot is explored to:

· Accelerate development of reconciliation services in .NET

· Auto-generate:

o Data comparison scripts

o Validation logic

o API integrations

· Improve developer productivity and consistency

5. Key Benefits

· Faster Mapping & Rule Generation using AI

· Improved Accuracy through automated reconciliation checks

· Reduced Manual Effort for schema mapping and validation

· Knowledge Extraction from business rules and legacy systems

· Enhanced Transparency via detailed reconciliation reports
6. Risks & Considerations

· LLM outputs require human validation/governance (human-in-the-loop)

· Complex transformations may need manual refinement

· Data privacy and security must be enforced (especially in Azure private cloud)

· Deterministic validation layers must exist alongside AI recommendations

Final Validation Summary

The use case is technically sound and highly relevant for large-scale bank mergers. The integration of Mistral (LLM) + GitHub Copilot + .NET is appropriate and the architecture correctly separates:

· AI (logic inference, mapping)

· Execution layer (data processing, reconciliation)

This solution positions:

· Mistral → Intelligence (mapping, rules, logic)

· GitHub Copilot → Developer productivity

· .NET + Azure → Execution + scalability

Together, they create a modern AI-powered reconciliation platform for hybrid (mainframe + open) systems.
